TULAREMIA, PRAIRIE DOGS - USA (TEXAS): OIE REPORT
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 1 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_47.HTM#Sec7>

Tularemia in Prairie Dogs in the United States of America
Follow-up report No. 1 (final report)
See also: 9 Aug 2002
Information received on 29 Oct 2002 from Dr Peter Fernandez, Associate
Administrator, Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service, United States
Department of Agriculture (USDA), Washington, DC:
End of previous report period: 8 Aug 2002 (see Disease Information, 15
[32], 153, dated 9 Aug 2002).
End of this report period: 28 Oct 2002.
The Texas Department of Health and the Centers for Disease Control
investigated an outbreak of tularemia in prairie dogs introduced into and
exported from an exotic animal export facility located in Denton County, Texas.
All of the prairie dogs were wild-caught in Texas and South Dakota. The
epizootic is believed to have started in mid-July 2002. All prairie dogs
that were shipped by the Texas facility after 16 Jun 2002 were recalled.
Total number of animals in the outbreak (updated data):
species : fau
susceptible: 3600
cases---
deaths:250
destroyed:163
slaughtered: 0
On 2-4 Aug 2002, 163 prairie dogs were destroyed. Of these, 30 were
confirmed positive for tularemia and 36 were presumptively positive.
Quarantine on the affected premises has been lifted.
